# Refs for Any Mutable Value

`useRef` isn't just for DOM nodes. You can use it to hold any value that you want to persist across renders without causing a re-render when it changes.

This is useful for:

* Storing timers or interval IDs.
* Keeping a reference to a previous value.
* Holding data that shouldn't trigger UI updates.

```jsx
const timerRef = useRef(null);

const startTimer = () => {
  timerRef.current = setInterval(() => console.log('tick'), 1000);
};

const stopTimer = () => {
  clearInterval(timerRef.current);
};
```

Changing `timerRef.current` does **not** cause the component to re-render.

slides.codeSnippet:
function Stopwatch() {
  const [time, setTime] = useState(0);
  const intervalRef = useRef(null);

  const start = () => {
    if (intervalRef.current !== null) return;
    intervalRef.current = setInterval(() => {
      setTime(t => t + 1);
    }, 1000);
  };

  const stop = () => {
    clearInterval(intervalRef.current);
    intervalRef.current = null;
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <p>Time: {time}s</p>
      <button onClick={start}>Start</button>
      <button onClick={stop}>Stop</button>
    </div>
  );
}
